{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592892"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:20:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15283"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15283"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.15,0.67,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7974"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64804"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7974"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15283"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6835"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"10332"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21479"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64804"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EReferred pain occurs when pain is perceived at a location other than the site of the painful stimulus. An inflamed gallbladder can cause referred pain due to its anatomical and neural connections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following descriptions is correct for any referred pain from an inflamed gallbladder?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Irritation of the left hemidiaphragm initiates the pain","Pain begins in the epigastric region and progresses to the left upper quadrant","Pain is referred to the left shoulder via the phrenic nerve","Right shoulder tip pain is characteristic due to diaphragm irritation","The vagus nerve is responsible for conveyance of the pain"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gallbladder is located in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen and closely adjacent to the diaphragm. Referred pain from the gallbladder is often felt in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E due to irritation of the diaphragm, which is innervated by the phrenic nerve. The phrenic nerve carries sensory information from the diaphragm to the cervical spinal cord segments, which also receive sensory input from the shoulder area, leading to the perception of pain in the shoulder. The \u003Cstrong\u003Evagus nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically involved in this referred pain pattern. Pain from the gallbladder does not typically progress to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft upper quadrant\u003C/strong\u003E or the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft shoulder\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Referred pain from the gallbladder is often felt in the right shoulder due to irritation of the diaphragm.","The phrenic nerve, which innervates the diaphragm, can convey referred pain to the shoulder."],"references":["Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15283"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50238"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T17:26:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T17:27:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7974"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64804"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":n